prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: To obtain the continuum at lambda~0.86 mm. We will use Band 7, centered on the Standard Sky Frequency of 343.5 GHz. We will exploit the band width of 1.9 GHz. Since our targets have no spectroscopic redshift measurements, we cannot tune the central wavelengths to detect particular lines, nonetheless, we expect to observe some molecular and atomic lines (e.g., CO from the J=4-3 to J=10-9, HCN, HCO+ and CI). If these lines will be detected, redshifts will be confirmed spectroscopically and the amount of dust and gas in galaxies will be constrained.
Since most of our sources are expected to be unresolved at ~350 GHz, we choose to adopt an angular resolution of 0.7", that is comparable to the UltraVISTA FWHM in the K band (Muzzin et al. 2013b).

The main task of our proposal is to robustly measure the emission of the continuum with S/N>5 at lambda~0.86 mm. We will use Band 7.
To estimate the expected flux densities for our targets we follow different approaches, and adopt the most conservative predictions to set our exposure times (see Fig. 1c). The first method uses the IR templates of Dale & Helou 2002 normalized at the observed MIPS 24 micron flux density to estimate the expected flux density in Band 7. The second method uses the MagPhys code by Da Cunha et al. 2008 to fit the observed SEDs from the UV to the 24 micron. The expected flux densities at lambda~0.86 mm are then derived directly from the best-fit models. Herschel-PACS photometry at 100 and/or 160 micron is available for 15% of the galaxies targeted by this proposal. Including PACS fluxes in SED modeling increases the expected fluxes at 0.86mm by ~40%. Based on these estimates, 42/76 (55%) galaxies in this science goal are expected to have a continuum flux density 0.6<S_1mm<1 mJy.
Given the uncertainties in the expected emission, our time estimates are calculated in order to obtain a uniform sensitivity for 42 targets in this science goal, with the conservative threshold that we will detect the faintest source at >5sigma significance. For the remaining 34 (45%), a non detection would yield a 5sigma upper limit on the ISM mass of 2x01^10 M_sun at z~2.
With the current setup, the estimated total time for this science goal is 6.57 hours, that is required to reach a 1-sigma continuum rms of 0.12 mJy for 42 targets and an upper limit for the remaining 34, assuming the weather conditions are in the 2th Octile (0.658 mm).
We will adopt system-defined calibration.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: When and how the most massive galaxies formed is one of the most unsolved problems in astrophysics. We built the first sample of progenitors of local ultra-massive galaxies (i.e., log(M*/M_sun)=11.8 at z=0; UMGs) out to z=3. While the stellar population properties (e.g. M* and SFR) of these galaxies and their evolution since z=3 is arguably robustly constrained, a measurement of their gas content and a characterization of their interstellar medium (ISM) are still missing, especially in the star-forming progenitors. Indeed, the ISM is the crucial ingredient fueling the activities of star formation and active galactic nuclei. We propose for 9.7 hours of ALMA observations in Band 7 to measure the long wavelength dust continuum to characterize the ISM (i.e. gas mass, gas fraction, gas depletion timescale) and to investigate its evolution since z=3 in a unique sample of progenitors of local UMGs. These observations will provide, for the first time, a comprehensive picture of both the stars and the gas during the most active period in the formation and assembly of today's most massive galaxies (i.e., 1<z<3).
